<subSubSection pageId="105" pageNumber="106" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="105.[189,303,823,849]" box="[189,303,823,849]" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,823,849]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,823,849]" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="105.[189,1399,870,1002]" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Marshall, 2019" authorityName="Marshall" authorityYear="2019" box="[488,620,870,896]" class="Insecta" family="Micropezidae" genus="Mesoconius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[488,620,870,896]" italics="true" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">M. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[627,721,870,896]" pageId="105" pageNumber="106" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, from which it differs in having the postocellar portion of the frontal vitta broad and not pointed, the parafacial and oviscape black, upper fronto-orbital bristles absent, the epicephalon smooth, and the mid and hind femora black almost to the apex. These species appear on the same branch of a CO1 tree, but they are deeply divergent (
<figureCitation box="[1040,1128,975,1002]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="123.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[189,1373,810,1883]" captionTargetId="figure@123.[189,1398,799,1896]" captionTargetPageId="123" captionText="Fig. 50. Maximum likelihood tree from CO1 barcodes. Sequences were aligned using BOLD (amino acid based HMM) and then manually corrected. Maximum likelihood analysis was performed in RAxML (ver. 8.2) using GTR-G with 100 replicates." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3402003/files/figure.png" pageId="105" pageNumber="106">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
